\begin_layout Subsection
Determinants of Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the good's price changes, it entails 2 effects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Income Effect: higher price reduces purchasing power, as if the income fails,
 thus demands falls (if it's normal) or rises (if it's inferior).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Substitution Effect: higher price makes other pruducts relatively cheaper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The price effect is the sum of these two, which usually has inverse correlation
 with price (demand curve has negative slope).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Preference - more (less) demand at any given price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changes in price affect the achieved level of utility, but do not reshape
 preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens to the demand curve of a good, when:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The income of the consumers rises? Shifts right, unless it's an inferior
 good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Price of a substitude good falls? Shifts left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Price of the good increases? Nothing (movement along the curve).
\end_layout

