\begin_layout Subsection
Costs Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Costs
\series default
 include both explicit (expenditure) and implicit (forgone income, potential
 rent/earnings).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: 2 firms with income=40, one rents office for 50, other one owns
 it.
 Both should shut down, the former one is explicit cost, in the latter one
 it's implicit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Total costs
\series default
 are the minimum required costs to produce any output level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fixed costs
\series default
 - paid for the fixed input, regardless of output level (rent).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Variable costs
\series default
 - costs of the variable input (labor).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Average cost
\series default
 - cost per unit (total cost / units number)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Marginal cost
\series default
 - change in total cost, as a result of marginal output increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Average cost curve is normally U-shaped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Economies of scale
\series default
 - average cost falls when output rises (specialization).
 This proprety is common in big corporations / monopolies.
 Huge fixed cost for initial setup, then, as it continues to expand - efficiency
 increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Constant return to scale 
\series default
- average cost is constant when output rises.
 The idea is that the output responds to scaling, and returns (ratio between
 output & input) are constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Diseconomies of scale
\series default
 - average cost rises when output rises (coordination).
\end_layout

