\begin_layout Subsection
Competitive Firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two key assumptions in the short-term: many buyers & many sellers; goods
 offered are the same.
 Thus, each agent is a 
\series bold
price taker
\series default
 - no 
\series bold
market power
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rational firms seek to maximize profit, where profit is revenues minus total
 costs, and revenues are market price times qunatity sold.
 The quantity sold (produced) is decided by the firm so that profit is maximized
 - 
\series bold
that's the key motivator for each decision
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Marginal revenue 
\series default
- how much total revenue changes, when selling one more unit.
 For competitive firm it's the price of the unit.
 Another unit will be produced, as long as the marginal revenue exceeds
 marginal cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimal ouptut is when price equal to the marginal cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Profit Maximization - Generalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimal output problem is maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $P\cdot X-TC(X)$
\end_inset

 i.e price times quantity, minus total cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First-order condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\frac{\partial TC(X)}{\partial X}=MC(X)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second-order condition is 
\begin_inset Formula $-MC'(X)<0$
\end_inset

, which means MC rises with output.
\end_layout

